                                    <p class="main-text">Grant element: </p>
                                    <br class="text-muted">
                                        The grant element measures the concessionality of a loan. It is defined as the difference between its nominal value (face value) and the sum of the discounted future debt-service payments (net present value) to be made by the borrower, expressed as a percentage of the face value of the loan:
                                        Whenever the interest rate charged for a loan is lower than the appropriate discount rate, the resulting present value of the debt is smaller than its face value, with the difference reflecting the grant element of the loan. Upfront commissions and/or management fees throughout the lifetime of the loan constitute a cost of contracting/managing the loan and therefore an implicit interest cost, which should be included in calculating the level of concessionality. This template takes into account such commissions and fees as well as alternative standard repayment profiles (equal principal payments, annuity based principal payments, lump-sum principal and interest payment at maturity, and a customizable schedule). It can also calculate the grant element for packages that combine a grant with a (non)concessional loan. For any given combination of interest rate, commission, and fees, the minimum grant element of 35 percent can be simulated by using the “goal seek” function, i.e., what would be the maximum interest rate, commission, or fee that would bring a hypothetical loan at or above the required 35 percent grant element. </br></br>
                                          <center> <img src="../assets/img/calcul.jpg" > </center>
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        The workbook contains an Input-Output sheet and six alternative worksheets that calculate the grant element for debt ceiling purposes based on (i) an equal principal repayment schedule (GE-Calculation Equal-PP); (ii) an annuity schedule (GE-Calculation Annuity); (iii) a lump sum principal payment at maturity (GE-Calculation Lump-Sum); (iv) a lump sum  principal and simple interest payment at maturity (GE-Calculation Lump-Sum P/I), (v) a lump sum  principal and compound interest payment at maturity (GE-Calculation Lump-Sum P/CompoundedI) and (vi) a manually entered debt service profile (GE-Calculation Custom) for loans that do not fit any of the standard terms, e.g. graduated principal repayment (most loans use the equal repayment schedule). All six worksheets allow for taking into account upfront commissions paid for contracting the loan and recurrent management fees of the loan. In cases where management fees are not paid on a set schedule, they have to be entered manually.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Two additional worksheets can be used to assess loans under Islamic law and other IsDB instruments.
                                    </p>
